# Cypress Test Structure & Types

## 1. File Organisation

| Test Type | File Pattern   | Location                       |
| --------- | -------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Unit      | `*.unit.cy.ts` | Co-located next to source file |
| Component | `*.cy.tsx`     | `tests/component/`             |
| E2E       | `*.cy.js`      | `tests/e2e/`                   |

### Unit Tests (`.unit.cy.ts`)
Test pure functions in isolation. Import directly and assert outputs.
Co-locate with source: `src/utils/foo.ts` -> `src/utils/foo.unit.cy.ts`

### Component Tests (`.cy.tsx`)
Mount components in isolation using `cy.mount`. Use spies for callback props.

### E2E Tests (`.cy.js`)
Test complete user flows with mocked network requests. Never hit real backends.

## 2. Test Hierarchy & Naming

Use `describe` blocks for features/components, `it` blocks for individual scenarios.

```typescript path=null start=null
// ✅ Good: Clear hierarchy & Behaviour-focused naming
describe('CanvasImage', () => {
  describe('zoom behaviour', () => {
    it('zooms in when scrolling up', () => { ... });
    it('respects maximum zoom limit of 5x', () => { ... });
  });
});
```

Test names must describe the **expected behaviour**, not the implementation.
*   ✅ `displays error message when login fails`
*   ❌ `calls setError with message`
